title: Nineteenth century letters,
author: Rees, Byron Johnson
snippet: I have thought he had a canine appetite for books, though this sometimes declines in the decline of life. I am beautifying my house in Green Street; a comfortable house is a great source of happiness. It ranks immediately after health and a good conscience.

title: Ghosts I have seen and other psychic experiences,
author: Tweedale, Violet
snippet: She has always been a great traveler, yet a delicate woman. Only her indomitable spirit kept her going in her youth, as it still does in her beautiful house in Green Street, and her model farm in Gloucestershire.

title: A holiday tour in Europe.
author: Cook, Joel
snippet: mostly one-horse vehicles, and the display, taken altogether, can hardly compare to a fine afternoon in Fairmount Park, where the handsome drive, and, in fact, the entire road from Green Street to George's Hill and back through the East Park is full of magnificent turnouts. Parisian horseflesh is generally poor, and this spoils the effect.

title: Hospitable England in the seventies;
author: Dana, Richard Henry
snippet: As the proceedings were dull and most of the important  members out of the House, Mr. Ferguson and I left and went to the house of a friend of his, a Dr. Jones, in Green Street, Park Square, for afternoon tea at five o'clock. It was a pleasant and agreeable family gathering.
